    <h2>Understanding Asset Division in Maryland Divorce</h2>
    <p>
      One of the most consequential aspects of any Maryland divorce is the division of marital assets and debts. Maryland follows the principle of <strong>equitable distribution</strong> — meaning the court divides marital property in a way it deems fair, based on a range of statutory factors. This does not necessarily mean a 50/50 split.
    </p>
    <p>
      At Child Custody with a Plan, our attorneys work meticulously to identify every marital asset, build a thorough picture of your financial situation, and develop a strategic approach to division that serves your long-term financial stability.
    </p>

    <h2>Marital Property vs. Non-Marital Property in Maryland</h2>
    <p>
      Before assets can be divided, they must be properly categorized. Maryland law distinguishes between:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Marital Property:</strong> Assets acquired by either or both spouses during the marriage, regardless of whose name is on the title. This typically includes the marital home, vehicles, retirement contributions made during the marriage, bank accounts, and investment accounts.</li>
      <li><strong>Non-Marital (Separate) Property:</strong> Assets owned before the marriage, or received during the marriage by gift or inheritance — provided they have not been commingled with marital funds.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Determining what is and isn't marital property can be complex, especially in long marriages or situations involving business interests and inherited assets. Our attorneys conduct thorough financial investigations to ensure every asset is properly classified.
    </p>

    <h2>Types of Assets We Handle</h2>

    <h3>The Marital Home</h3>
    <p>
      The family home is often the most valuable marital asset and the most emotionally charged. Options in Maryland include one spouse buying out the other's equity, selling the home and dividing proceeds, or — in limited circumstances — one spouse continuing to occupy the home temporarily post-divorce. Our attorneys help you evaluate which option best serves your financial and personal goals.
    </p>

    <h3>Retirement Accounts & Pensions</h3>
    <p>
      Retirement assets accumulated during the marriage are typically marital property in Maryland. Dividing 401(k)s, IRAs, pensions, and other retirement accounts often requires a Qualified Domestic Relations Order (QDRO). Our attorneys work with financial professionals to ensure retirement assets are divided accurately and tax-efficiently.
    </p>

    <h3>Investment Accounts & Brokerage Accounts</h3>
    <p>
      Investment portfolios, brokerage accounts, stocks, bonds, and other securities acquired during the marriage are subject to equitable distribution. We work to ensure accurate valuation and strategic allocation of these assets.
    </p>

    <h3>Bank Accounts & Cash Assets</h3>
    <p>
      Joint and individual checking, savings, and money market accounts must be evaluated for marital contribution. We trace the origin of funds to ensure proper classification and distribution.
    </p>

    <h3>Business Interests</h3>
    <p>
      When one or both spouses own a business, its marital value must be determined. We work with professional business valuators to establish a defensible valuation. For more detail, see our <a href="/divorces-involving-businesses" class="text-teal-600 hover:underline">Divorces Involving Businesses</a> practice area.
    </p>

    <h2>Factors Maryland Courts Consider in Asset Division</h2>
    <p>Maryland courts weigh several factors when determining equitable distribution, including:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>The contributions of each spouse to the marital property (financial and non-financial)</li>
      <li>The duration of the marriage</li>
      <li>The economic circumstances of each spouse at the time of divorce</li>
      <li>The circumstances that contributed to the estrangement</li>
      <li>How and when the assets were acquired</li>
      <li>The age, physical, and mental condition of both spouses</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Our attorneys build a comprehensive record of your contributions — financial and non-financial — to present the strongest possible equitable distribution argument.
    </p>

    <h2>Marital Debt Division</h2>
    <p>
      Maryland courts also address marital debts in the divorce proceeding. Mortgages, credit card debt, car loans, student loans, and other liabilities acquired during the marriage are subject to equitable allocation. We fight to ensure that debt is assigned fairly and that you are protected from future liability for debts assigned to your spouse.
    </p>

